    "body": "Yes! I think this would be a handy feature.\r\n\r\nCan you tell us how you imagine this working? I guess that we could accomplish this with snapshots if they worked in a different way than they do now.\r\n\r\n1. The chain is at block 1000. You take a snapshot `A`.\r\n2. You mine 2 blocks and take another snapshot `B`.\r\n3. You revert to the snapshot `A`. The latest block is again 1000.\r\n4. You mine 4 blocks (and the first two are different than the ones you mined in step 2).\r\n5. You take a snapshot `C`.\r\n\r\nNow you can go to snapshot `B` and then move to `C` to simulate a reorg.\r\n\r\nThis can't be done with our current implementation of snapshots because when you revert to `A` in step 3, the snapshot `B` is discarded.\r\n\r\nAlso, this is very convoluted. But it could be a building block on top of which something more ergonomic could be built (for example: a method that takes a block number and a group of transactions, and simulates a reorg by going back to that block number and mining all those transactions).",
